00:02:24.630 --> 00:02:26.630
See you next time.

00:02:26.630 --> 00:02:29.390
Love you, Twizzlers.

00:02:29.390 --> 00:02:30.390
Pull and peel.

00:02:30.390 --> 00:02:31.390
Pull and peel.

00:02:31.390 --> 00:02:32.390
Pull and peel.

00:02:32.390 --> 00:02:33.390
I make toys.

00:02:33.390 --> 00:02:34.390
We play games.

00:02:34.390 --> 00:02:38.400
I got an A plus.

00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:40.400
He loves me not.

00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:42.400
No batteries needed.

00:02:42.400 --> 00:02:45.320
Blurs, pull and peel.

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:49.320
Chewy, delicious cherry flavored candy with nothing to pick up.

00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:59.070
Mr. Franklin, I'm surprised.

00:02:59.070 --> 00:03:01.070
I finished my report, sir.

00:03:01.070 --> 00:03:02.070
No, I'm referring to your Apple Jacks.

00:03:02.070 --> 00:03:03.070
You love them.

00:03:03.070 --> 00:03:05.070
Yes, Mr. Williams, you would.

00:03:05.070 --> 00:03:08.070
It seems to me something called Apple Jacks should.

00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:09.070
Tastes like apple.

00:03:09.070 --> 00:03:10.070
Precisely.

00:03:10.070 --> 00:03:12.070
Are they supposed to taste like apple?

00:03:12.070 --> 00:03:13.070
Keep eating.

00:03:13.070 --> 00:03:14.070
That isn't why we like them.

00:03:14.070 --> 00:03:16.070
Enlighten me.

00:03:17.070 --> 00:03:20.070
Uh, we just do.

00:03:20.070 --> 00:03:21.070
Yeah.

00:03:22.070 --> 00:03:25.070
Kill lots of Apple Jacks cereal is part of this complete breakfast.

00:03:25.070 --> 00:03:26.070
We love it.

00:03:26.070 --> 00:03:28.670
Pop in.

00:03:28.670 --> 00:03:29.670
We're going up one.

00:03:29.670 --> 00:03:30.670
Where?

00:03:30.670 --> 00:03:39.540
The barbie.

00:03:39.540 --> 00:03:41.860
And apple pie.

00:03:41.860 --> 00:03:48.330
On the grill.

00:03:48.330 --> 00:03:52.560
We order.

00:03:52.560 --> 00:03:53.560
More apple pie.

00:03:53.560 --> 00:03:55.560
The barbie McDonald's restaurant play set with drive-thru that really talks.

00:03:55.560 --> 00:03:57.560
You put it together, dolls and car not included.

00:03:57.560 --> 00:04:12.010
Saturday night, Nickelodeon.

00:04:12.010 --> 00:04:16.010
Now you'll know what everyone's talking about on Monday morning.

00:04:16.010 --> 00:04:21.140
There's nothing wrong with your TV.

00:04:21.140 --> 00:04:23.140
I'm in black and white for a reason.

00:04:23.140 --> 00:04:26.140
I'm demonstrating how you can take something old, like a black and white movie,

00:04:26.140 --> 00:04:28.140
and suddenly make it seem new again.

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:31.140
All through the modern miracle of colorization.

00:04:32.140 --> 00:04:33.140
Voila.

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:34.140
Here I am.

00:04:35.140 --> 00:04:39.140
Of course, this colorization technique isn't always totally accurate.

00:04:39.140 --> 00:04:42.290
There.

00:04:42.290 --> 00:04:43.290
That's better.

00:04:43.290 --> 00:04:46.290
At least it's one way to make something old look like something new.

00:04:46.290 --> 00:04:51.820
And that's exactly what I have to do for Mr. Batenback's history class.

00:04:51.820 --> 00:04:54.820
Take something old, tired and worn out, and reinvent it.

00:04:54.820 --> 00:04:57.820
Well, you can't get more worn out than these sneakers.

00:04:57.820 --> 00:05:00.820
But with a little help from Dad's trusty magic markers?

00:05:01.820 --> 00:05:02.820
Good as new.

00:05:02.820 --> 00:05:03.820
Only better.

00:05:03.820 --> 00:05:05.820
And what about these jeans?

00:05:05.820 --> 00:05:07.820
You've seen them once, you've seen them a thousand times,

00:05:07.820 --> 00:05:09.820
but by just roughing them up.

00:05:11.820 --> 00:05:14.820
Now new jeans look like old jeans, which makes them even newer jeans.

00:05:14.820 --> 00:05:16.820
It's a whole new concept.

00:05:16.820 --> 00:05:19.820
I guess it's just a matter of looking at an old thing in a new light.

00:05:20.820 --> 00:05:22.820
Sis, can I borrow five bucks?

00:05:22.820 --> 00:05:23.820
I'd ask.

00:05:23.820 --> 00:05:26.820
I wanted to do you the favor of helping you establish credit

00:05:26.820 --> 00:05:28.820
with the future financial giant.

00:05:28.820 --> 00:05:30.820
Let me take a nanosecond to think about it.

00:05:30.820 --> 00:05:31.820
No!

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:38.830
Maybe some things aren't worth changing.

00:05:38.830 --> 00:05:41.830
In that case, it's best just to get rid of them.

00:05:41.830 --> 00:05:44.830
So, off with the old and on with the new.

00:05:44.830 --> 00:06:38.290
Chocolate chip-flavored postage stamps?

00:06:39.290 --> 00:06:43.290
Pairs of socks that attract each other with hidden magnets.

00:06:43.290 --> 00:06:45.290
Could be. I'll write that one down.

00:06:46.290 --> 00:06:47.290
Here's one.

00:06:47.290 --> 00:06:50.290
Jelly beans that don't roll off your desk because they're flat like pancakes.

00:06:50.290 --> 00:06:54.290
How about pancakes that don't stick to the ceiling because they're shaped like jelly beans?

00:06:54.290 --> 00:06:57.290
Damn, why would pancakes be stuck to the ceiling in the first place?

00:06:57.290 --> 00:06:59.290
I don't know. I just thought it'd be fun.

00:07:00.290 --> 00:07:04.290
Well, maybe we should try to improve something that actually has something to do with the real world.

00:07:04.290 --> 00:07:07.290
You know, something that could actually make our lives better.

00:07:07.290 --> 00:07:10.290
Mr. Bowdenback just wants us to take something old and make it new.

00:07:10.290 --> 00:07:12.290
How can that improve our lives?

00:07:12.290 --> 00:07:14.290
Well, if it's something old and really annoying,

00:07:14.290 --> 00:07:17.290
we can make it new by getting rid of the annoying part.

00:07:17.290 --> 00:07:19.290
Hey, I know.

00:07:19.290 --> 00:07:22.290
Isn't it really annoying the way you can never get a roll of toilet paper started

00:07:22.290 --> 00:07:25.290
without ripping the first few sheets to shreds?

00:07:25.290 --> 00:07:27.290
New and improved toilet paper?

00:07:27.290 --> 00:07:29.290
Not great, but better.

00:07:29.290 --> 00:07:31.290
I've got an idea.

00:07:31.290 --> 00:07:35.290
What's the most annoying, obnoxious, irritating thing about school assemblies?

00:07:35.290 --> 00:07:38.290
Mrs. Pringle twickers' beautiful thoughts of the day.

00:07:38.290 --> 00:07:40.290
That's pretty annoying.

00:07:40.290 --> 00:07:43.290
That's true, but I'm talking about the school anthem.

00:07:56.290 --> 00:07:59.290
If that ancient excuse for a song doesn't need improving, I don't know what does.

00:07:59.290 --> 00:08:01.290
Hey, we can give it rhythm. We can give it soul.

00:08:01.290 --> 00:08:03.290
We can give it that hip-hop happening sound.

00:08:03.290 --> 00:08:06.290
Maybe even a few lyrics besides Thomas Tumper High.

00:08:06.290 --> 00:08:09.290
Who says you can't teach an old song new tricks?

00:08:09.290 --> 00:08:11.290
So let's improve the anthem.

00:08:11.290 --> 00:08:13.290
Great. We can work on it now.

00:08:13.290 --> 00:08:16.290
Okay, but first I've got to run to the one-hour photo place.

00:08:16.290 --> 00:08:17.290
What for?

00:08:17.290 --> 00:08:20.290
My dad dropped off some pictures of him and that guy from the Highlight Halftime show.

00:08:20.290 --> 00:08:21.290
Wow.

00:08:21.290 --> 00:08:23.290
So I promised him I'd pick him up.

00:08:23.290 --> 00:08:25.290
Okay.

00:08:25.290 --> 00:08:27.290
I'll know the azuki beans.

00:08:27.290 --> 00:08:29.290
The what?

00:08:29.290 --> 00:08:31.290
I promised my mom I'd pick him up for dinner.

00:08:31.290 --> 00:08:33.290
She's really going to be steamed.

00:08:33.290 --> 00:08:35.290
What's the big deal? It's just beans.

00:08:35.290 --> 00:08:37.290
That's the problem. It's not just beans.

00:08:37.290 --> 00:08:40.290
Okay. I forgot to program the VCR to tape that painting show.

00:08:40.290 --> 00:08:42.290
A dab here, a dab there.

00:08:42.290 --> 00:08:45.290
And two days ago she was picking me up and I was a half an hour late.

00:08:45.290 --> 00:08:47.290
I'd been forgetting her stuff all week.

00:08:47.290 --> 00:08:49.290
Well, we've been kind of busy at school.

00:08:49.290 --> 00:08:52.290
Yeah, but now mom won't be able to make her azuki bean burritos.

00:08:52.290 --> 00:08:54.290
Azuki bean burritos?

00:08:54.290 --> 00:08:56.290
Makes you appreciate frozen pizza.

00:08:56.290 --> 00:08:59.290
Yeah. And some old things you don't want to make new.

00:08:59.290 --> 00:09:00.290
Like what?

00:09:00.290 --> 00:09:02.290
Mom's leftovers.

00:09:02.290 --> 00:09:03.290
I better get going.

00:09:03.290 --> 00:09:26.620
See you later.

00:09:26.620 --> 00:09:28.620
What are you doing? I've been looking all over for you.

00:09:28.620 --> 00:09:31.620
Oh, um, oh, it's nothing. I've been here all the time.

00:09:31.620 --> 00:09:33.620
Well, didn't you hear me call?

00:09:33.620 --> 00:09:36.620
Well, I guess I just got absorbed in what I was doing.

00:09:36.620 --> 00:09:39.620
Mom, I forgot the azuki beans.

00:09:39.620 --> 00:09:41.620
What's that?

00:09:41.620 --> 00:09:44.620
I know you asked me to pick them up and I know I've been forgetting stuff all week,

00:09:44.620 --> 00:09:45.620
but I've been really busy at school.

00:09:45.620 --> 00:09:46.620
Oh, don't worry about it.

00:09:46.620 --> 00:09:48.620
I can go get them now.

00:09:48.620 --> 00:09:50.620
Oh, never mind you. I know how busy you are.

00:09:50.620 --> 00:09:51.620
But...

00:09:51.620 --> 00:09:52.620
It's no big deal.

00:09:52.620 --> 00:09:53.620
But I...

00:09:53.620 --> 00:09:55.620
I can make do with that.

00:09:55.620 --> 00:09:58.620
Mom, are you okay?

00:09:58.620 --> 00:10:00.620
I'm fine.

00:10:00.620 --> 00:10:02.620
Okay, I'm going now.

00:10:02.620 --> 00:10:03.620
Okay.

00:10:03.620 --> 00:10:04.620
I'll see you later.

00:10:04.620 --> 00:10:05.620
Okay.

00:10:05.620 --> 00:10:06.620
Yell if you need anything.

00:10:06.620 --> 00:10:07.620
Okay, dear.

00:10:07.620 --> 00:10:08.620
Yell if you don't need anything.

00:10:08.620 --> 00:10:09.620
Okay.

00:10:09.620 --> 00:10:13.620
Yell if my real mom has been kidnapped by aliens and you're a pod person.

00:10:13.620 --> 00:10:14.620
Okay.

00:10:14.620 --> 00:10:24.700
Ferguson, that's your fifth lemonade break in an hour.

00:10:24.700 --> 00:10:25.700
Dad.

00:10:25.700 --> 00:10:27.700
We deserve a break.

00:10:27.700 --> 00:10:29.700
Refinishing furniture is hard work.

00:10:29.700 --> 00:10:31.700
I think these fumes are starting to get to me.

00:10:31.700 --> 00:10:32.700
I guess I'll have some too.

00:10:32.700 --> 00:10:33.700
There you go.

00:10:33.700 --> 00:10:34.700
Thanks.

00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:36.700
You know, Ferguson, I really appreciate you pitching in to help.

00:10:36.700 --> 00:10:38.700
Oh, sure.

00:10:38.700 --> 00:10:39.700
No way I figure it.

00:10:39.700 --> 00:10:43.700
However much we sell this worthless old furniture for is pure profit.

00:10:43.700 --> 00:10:46.700
Ferguson, we are not selling this worthless old furniture.

00:10:46.700 --> 00:10:48.700
I happen to love this worthless old furniture.

00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:49.700
Dad.

00:10:49.700 --> 00:10:50.700
Dad.

00:10:50.700 --> 00:10:51.700
Dad.

00:10:51.700 --> 00:10:54.700
Love and profit have nothing to do with one another.

00:10:54.700 --> 00:10:57.700
I mean, we deserve something for our manual labor.

00:10:57.700 --> 00:11:00.700
Well, how about the satisfaction of a job well done?

00:11:00.700 --> 00:11:01.700
All right.

00:11:01.700 --> 00:11:02.700
One old chair.

00:11:02.700 --> 00:11:03.700
Just let me sell off one old chair.

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:05.700
Yeah, I'll think about it.

00:11:05.700 --> 00:11:06.700
Hey.

00:11:06.700 --> 00:11:07.700
Hi, Clarissa.

00:11:07.700 --> 00:11:08.700
Would you like some lemonade?

00:11:08.700 --> 00:11:12.700
Or perhaps I could interest you in a beautiful antique chair

00:11:12.700 --> 00:11:14.700
expertly refinished by skilled artisans.

00:11:14.700 --> 00:11:16.700
Notice the faux graining.

00:11:16.700 --> 00:11:18.700
Thanks, but I think I'll stick with the lemonade.

00:11:18.700 --> 00:11:19.700
All right.

00:11:19.700 --> 00:11:21.700
Dad, don't let Ferguson tuck you into anything.

00:11:21.700 --> 00:11:22.700
What?

00:11:22.700 --> 00:11:25.700
No, Ferguson would never talk me in anything, would you?

00:11:25.700 --> 00:11:26.700
Never.

00:11:26.700 --> 00:11:27.700
Here you go.

00:11:27.700 --> 00:11:29.700
Expertly squeezed by a skilled sucker.

00:11:29.700 --> 00:11:30.700
Thanks.

00:11:30.700 --> 00:11:33.700
Hey, Dad, have you noticed anything different about Mom?

00:11:33.700 --> 00:11:34.700
No.

00:11:34.700 --> 00:11:35.700
Why?

00:11:35.700 --> 00:11:36.700
What about you, Ferguson?

00:11:36.700 --> 00:11:37.700
Hmm.

00:11:37.700 --> 00:11:39.700
Did she cut her hair?

00:11:39.700 --> 00:11:43.700
You know us guys don't notice those things.

00:11:43.700 --> 00:11:46.700
Yeah, so neither of you noticed anything different.

00:11:46.700 --> 00:11:47.700
No?

00:11:47.700 --> 00:11:48.700
No, no.

00:11:48.700 --> 00:11:49.700
She seems fine.

00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:50.700
Well, just wondering.

00:11:50.700 --> 00:11:54.700
I mean, Mom's been real busy lately, but that's natural.

00:11:54.700 --> 00:11:56.700
Uh, Ferguson, can you pass me that rag?

00:11:56.700 --> 00:11:57.700
Sure, Dad.

00:11:57.700 --> 00:11:58.700
Thanks.

00:11:58.700 --> 00:12:00.700
OK, Ferguson, back to work.

00:12:00.700 --> 00:12:02.700
But I haven't finished my lemonade.

00:12:02.700 --> 00:12:03.700
Come on, Ferguson.

00:12:03.700 --> 00:12:11.020
Oh, right, Ferguson.

00:12:11.020 --> 00:12:13.020
Mom, you dropped one of yours.

00:12:13.020 --> 00:12:18.580
To the best mom in the world.

00:12:18.580 --> 00:12:19.580
Every day is your day.

00:12:19.580 --> 00:12:21.580
You are loved by all.

00:12:21.580 --> 00:12:22.580
Weird.

00:12:22.580 --> 00:12:23.580
What is this?

00:12:23.580 --> 00:12:24.580
A Mother's Day card?

00:12:24.580 --> 00:12:26.580
Did we forget Mother's Day?

00:12:26.580 --> 00:12:28.580
When is Mother's Day?

00:12:28.580 --> 00:12:30.580
And who is she making this card for?

00:12:30.580 --> 00:12:33.580
It must be for the kids at the Children's Museum to copy.

00:12:33.580 --> 00:12:36.580
She couldn't be making it for herself.

00:12:36.580 --> 00:12:38.580
Could she?

00:12:38.580 --> 00:12:44.650
Now, where did I put that date book?

00:12:44.650 --> 00:12:46.650
Hi, Sam.

00:12:46.650 --> 00:12:48.650
Hi, Clarissa.

00:12:48.650 --> 00:12:52.500
How come nobody told me it's Mother's Day?

00:12:52.500 --> 00:12:54.500
Well, because it's not.

00:12:54.500 --> 00:12:55.500
Are you sure?

00:12:55.500 --> 00:12:56.500
Sure, I'm sure.

00:12:56.500 --> 00:12:57.500
Pretty sure.

00:12:57.500 --> 00:13:00.500
My mom always calls me from the road on Mother's Day.

00:13:00.500 --> 00:13:01.500
I think she called me.

00:13:01.500 --> 00:13:02.500
Well, it's not this Sunday.

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:05.500
It's not next Sunday or the Sunday after that.

00:13:05.500 --> 00:13:06.500
Or that.

00:13:06.500 --> 00:13:07.500
Or that.

00:13:07.500 --> 00:13:09.500
When is Mother's Day anyway?

00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:11.500
Why are you so anxious for it to be Mother's Day?

00:13:11.500 --> 00:13:14.500
If it's not Mother's Day, my mom's getting weird on me.

00:13:14.500 --> 00:13:19.100
Look at what she was working on all afternoon.

00:13:19.100 --> 00:13:21.100
To the best mom in the world.

00:13:21.100 --> 00:13:24.100
Why would your mom be making a Mother's Day card?

00:13:24.100 --> 00:13:25.100
Good question.

00:13:25.100 --> 00:13:27.100
Maybe it's for her mom.

00:13:27.100 --> 00:13:29.100
But it's not Mother's Day.

00:13:29.100 --> 00:13:30.100
All right.

00:13:30.100 --> 00:13:32.100
Well, is she the type of person

00:13:32.100 --> 00:13:34.100
who buys Christmas presents in July?

00:13:34.100 --> 00:13:36.100
Maybe she's just planning ahead.

00:13:36.100 --> 00:13:37.100
You know, Sam,

00:13:37.100 --> 00:13:40.100
I've got the funniest feeling she's making cards for herself.

00:13:40.100 --> 00:13:41.100
What?

00:13:41.100 --> 00:13:42.100
And I think I'm to blame.

00:13:42.100 --> 00:13:43.100
How?

00:13:43.100 --> 00:13:45.100
All that stuff I've been forgetting.

00:13:45.100 --> 00:13:46.100
That doesn't sound so bad.

00:13:46.100 --> 00:13:48.100
Is there anything else?

00:13:48.100 --> 00:13:50.100
Besides forgetting stuff?

00:13:50.100 --> 00:13:52.100
Well, let's see.

00:13:52.100 --> 00:13:54.100
She did get kind of quiet last night at dinner

00:13:54.100 --> 00:13:57.100
when I mentioned taking the PSATs and then going to college.

00:13:57.100 --> 00:13:58.100
That's it.

00:13:58.100 --> 00:13:59.100
That's it.

00:13:59.100 --> 00:14:00.100
ENS.

00:14:00.100 --> 00:14:01.100
ENS?

00:14:01.100 --> 00:14:02.100
Okay.

00:14:02.100 --> 00:14:03.100
What is ENS?

00:14:03.100 --> 00:14:04.100
Empty Ness Syndrome.

00:14:04.100 --> 00:14:06.100
Empty Ness Syndrome?

00:14:06.100 --> 00:14:07.100
You know,

00:14:07.100 --> 00:14:09.100
when the little itsy-bitsy baby birds

00:14:09.100 --> 00:14:11.100
go up to learn how to flap their little wings,

00:14:11.100 --> 00:14:13.100
we'll soon they'll take off in the room.

00:14:13.100 --> 00:14:16.100
The big old mommy bird has a big old empty nest.

00:14:16.100 --> 00:14:17.100
No one to feed worms to.

00:14:17.100 --> 00:14:19.100
So you think my mom's afraid

00:14:19.100 --> 00:14:21.100
that we're all going to be leaving the nest soon?

00:14:21.100 --> 00:14:22.100
That's right.

00:14:22.100 --> 00:14:24.100
She's feeling unwanted, unneeded.

00:14:24.100 --> 00:14:26.100
She's wondering what to do with those worms.

00:14:26.100 --> 00:14:28.100
But my mom's so independent.

00:14:28.100 --> 00:14:29.100
Plus I'm not even gone yet.

00:14:29.100 --> 00:14:30.100
And there'll still be Ferguson.

00:14:30.100 --> 00:14:31.100
Nobody can forget that.

00:14:31.100 --> 00:14:33.100
I know he can't wait till I leave.

00:14:33.100 --> 00:14:36.100
So should I go get my dad's book on ENS

00:14:36.100 --> 00:14:38.100
or do you just want to work on our school anthem?

00:14:38.100 --> 00:14:40.100
Let's just work on the anthem.

00:14:40.100 --> 00:14:42.100
How about, uh,

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:47.060
oh, mom, what's wrong with her?

00:14:47.060 --> 00:14:49.060
I'll just be getting those books.

00:14:49.060 --> 00:14:50.060
Thanks, Sam.

00:14:50.060 --> 00:14:54.260
Hi, Clarissa.

00:14:54.260 --> 00:14:56.730
We love you.

00:14:56.730 --> 00:14:58.730
We don't want to leave.

00:14:58.730 --> 00:14:59.730
Who's leaving?

00:14:59.730 --> 00:15:00.730
Not me.

00:15:00.730 --> 00:15:01.730
That's for sure.

00:15:01.730 --> 00:15:02.730
Lisa, are you okay?

00:15:02.730 --> 00:15:03.730
Yeah, great.

00:15:03.730 --> 00:15:04.730
Are you?

00:15:04.730 --> 00:15:05.730
Fine.

00:15:05.730 --> 00:15:06.730
Listen, I just want to let you know

00:15:06.730 --> 00:15:08.730
I won't be home for dinner.

00:15:08.730 --> 00:15:10.730
You won't be home for dinner?

00:15:10.730 --> 00:15:11.730
Well, you're not the only ones

00:15:11.730 --> 00:15:13.730
who lead independent lives of your own.

00:15:13.730 --> 00:15:15.730
But I know you guys can pen for yourselves.

00:15:15.730 --> 00:15:16.730
But we can't pen for ourselves

00:15:16.730 --> 00:15:18.730
as well as you can pen for ourselves.

00:15:18.730 --> 00:15:20.730
You'll be fine.

00:15:20.730 --> 00:15:22.730
What's the basket for?

00:15:22.730 --> 00:15:23.730
Oh, it's just a little something

00:15:23.730 --> 00:15:25.730
I'm doing to make someone feel good.

00:15:25.730 --> 00:15:27.730
You mean it makes you feel good?

00:15:27.730 --> 00:15:29.730
Well, yes.

00:15:29.730 --> 00:15:32.730
In a way, it does make me feel good.

00:15:32.730 --> 00:15:33.730
Clarissa?

00:15:33.730 --> 00:15:35.730
The castle on the bottom of the fridge

00:15:35.730 --> 00:15:37.730
will be delicious heated up.

00:15:37.730 --> 00:15:41.710
Thanks, Mom.

00:15:41.710 --> 00:15:43.710
Well, it looks like Mom's overcompensating

00:15:43.710 --> 00:15:44.710
for this ENS thing

00:15:44.710 --> 00:15:46.710
by flying the coop herself.

00:15:46.710 --> 00:15:48.710
I better do something fast

00:15:48.710 --> 00:15:50.710
before she gets any more cuckoo.

00:15:50.710 --> 00:16:01.020
For Clarissa, more Snake after this.

00:16:01.020 --> 00:16:29.350
Camp Nowhere, rated PG,

00:16:29.350 --> 00:16:33.910
starts Friday, August 26th.

00:16:33.910 --> 00:16:35.910
Totally bored.

00:16:35.910 --> 00:16:37.910
Okay, somebody get the food.

00:16:37.910 --> 00:16:38.910
You got the apple jacks.

00:16:38.910 --> 00:16:39.910
Yes!

00:16:39.910 --> 00:16:40.910
What are you dweebs doing?

00:16:40.910 --> 00:16:42.910
Say your beeswax.

00:16:42.910 --> 00:16:43.910
You like that stuff?

00:16:43.910 --> 00:16:44.910
We love it.

00:16:44.910 --> 00:16:45.910
It's called apple jacks, you know?

00:16:45.910 --> 00:16:46.910
Really?

00:16:46.910 --> 00:16:47.910
And it doesn't taste like apple.

00:16:47.910 --> 00:16:49.910
That isn't why we like it anyway.

00:16:49.910 --> 00:16:51.910
Really? Then why?

00:16:53.910 --> 00:16:55.910
None of your beeswax.

00:16:55.910 --> 00:16:56.910
Yeah!

00:16:56.910 --> 00:16:57.910
Calyx, apple jack,

00:16:57.910 --> 00:16:59.910
carrot, as far as it's complete breakfast,

00:16:59.910 --> 00:17:00.910
we eat what we like.

00:17:00.910 --> 00:17:04.640
I think it's every parent's dream,

00:17:04.640 --> 00:17:07.640
maybe, to have a doctor in the family.

00:17:07.640 --> 00:17:34.370
Watching.

00:17:34.370 --> 00:17:35.370
Snake!

00:17:35.370 --> 00:17:38.370
And now, back to Clarissa explains it all.

00:17:44.370 --> 00:17:47.420
Okay.

00:17:47.420 --> 00:17:49.420
I think it's time for a darling family update.

00:17:49.420 --> 00:17:51.420
Here's what's been happening.

00:17:51.420 --> 00:17:53.420
Sam and I are still trying to come up

00:17:53.420 --> 00:17:55.420
with a school anthem you can groove to.

00:17:55.420 --> 00:17:58.420
Thomas Tupper High.

00:17:58.420 --> 00:18:00.420
Thomas Tupper High.

00:18:00.420 --> 00:18:02.420
Oh Lord, oh God,

00:18:02.420 --> 00:18:03.420
Tupper High.

00:18:03.420 --> 00:18:04.420
Supper High.

00:18:05.420 --> 00:18:06.420
Supper High.

00:18:08.420 --> 00:18:09.420
Dior High.

00:18:10.420 --> 00:18:13.420
Ferguson and Dad's idea of fixing up old chairs

00:18:13.420 --> 00:18:16.420
is turning into a brush with disaster.

00:18:26.540 --> 00:18:28.540
Mom's tearing through the arts and crafts bin

00:18:28.540 --> 00:18:30.540
for the mother's day in her mind.

00:18:31.540 --> 00:18:33.540
Hey, give the gift that keeps on giving

00:18:33.540 --> 00:18:35.540
the one you give yourself.

00:18:36.540 --> 00:18:38.540
Do I mind that my mom flipped out?

00:18:38.540 --> 00:18:39.540
Yes.

00:18:39.540 --> 00:18:40.540
Diagnosis.

00:18:40.540 --> 00:18:43.940
major bad case of ENS, empty nest syndrome.

00:18:43.940 --> 00:18:46.180
So what's a poor daughter to do?

00:18:46.180 --> 00:18:48.220
Count the days till I leave for good?

00:18:48.220 --> 00:18:49.580
I've got a better idea.

00:18:49.580 --> 00:18:51.060
I've hatched a plan.

00:18:51.060 --> 00:18:53.740
I'm about to make my mom feel so needed in her nest,

00:18:53.740 --> 00:18:59.140
the only thing she'll need will be a break.

00:18:59.140 --> 00:19:02.570
Hi, Mom.

00:19:02.570 --> 00:19:03.770
I don't know what it is with my hair,

00:19:03.770 --> 00:19:06.890
but do you think I could give me a hand?

00:19:06.890 --> 00:19:09.690
Oh, well, sure.

00:19:09.690 --> 00:19:10.890
I haven't brushed your hair for you

00:19:10.890 --> 00:19:12.250
since you were a little girl.

00:19:12.250 --> 00:19:15.050
You were always so much better at it than I was.

00:19:15.050 --> 00:19:18.850
Maybe you could braid it.

00:19:18.850 --> 00:19:20.770
You want me to braid your hair?

00:19:20.770 --> 00:19:22.130
You used to braid it for me.

00:19:22.130 --> 00:19:24.010
Well, not since you were five years old.

00:19:24.010 --> 00:19:26.010
Well, who says those days have to end?

00:19:26.010 --> 00:19:26.930
I miss those days.

00:19:26.930 --> 00:19:28.530
I miss those braids.

00:19:28.530 --> 00:19:32.410
Well, I'm sure you know how to braid your hair yourself.

00:19:32.410 --> 00:19:34.330
Oh, let me get that lemonade.

00:19:34.330 --> 00:19:36.610
Ferguson, we haven't even started working yet.

00:19:36.610 --> 00:19:39.930
Oh, yeah, I know, Dad, but I need to build up my energy.

00:19:39.930 --> 00:19:41.970
I'm still worn out from yesterday.

00:19:41.970 --> 00:19:44.130
Honestly, I did not know this project was

00:19:44.170 --> 00:19:45.090
going to take this long.

00:19:45.090 --> 00:19:46.890
Yeah, well, maybe if we took fewer breaks, you know.

00:19:46.890 --> 00:19:49.730
Dad, the more we energize, the more productive

00:19:49.730 --> 00:19:52.050
we'll be once we finally get started.

00:19:52.050 --> 00:19:56.650
Hey, Ferguson, maybe Mom could help you be more productive.

00:19:56.650 --> 00:19:58.090
Your mom's busy, Clarissa.

00:19:58.090 --> 00:20:00.050
Yeah, and I'm playing productive when I want to be.

00:20:00.050 --> 00:20:01.050
Oh, really?

00:20:01.050 --> 00:20:02.730
Well, that's because Mom, after all,

00:20:02.730 --> 00:20:05.490
she's the one who taught us how to flap our wings.

00:20:05.490 --> 00:20:08.970
I mean, Mom's always got a few good pointers.

00:20:08.970 --> 00:20:10.850
Clarissa, what are you talking about?

00:20:10.850 --> 00:20:13.410
Mom, Ferguson needs you to teach

00:20:13.410 --> 00:20:15.210
him how to be productive.

00:20:15.210 --> 00:20:16.770
I do not.

00:20:16.770 --> 00:20:18.330
Oh, yes, you do.

00:20:18.330 --> 00:20:21.850
Mom, we love your pep talks.

00:20:21.850 --> 00:20:23.010
Pep talks?

00:20:23.010 --> 00:20:27.570
Yeah, we depend on you to keep us going, right, Ferguson?

00:20:27.570 --> 00:20:29.090
You're sending in your eye?

00:20:29.090 --> 00:20:30.530
No.

00:20:30.530 --> 00:20:32.810
I mean, yeah, Mom, I need you to help me get something

00:20:32.810 --> 00:20:34.410
out of my eye.

00:20:34.410 --> 00:20:35.610
What's with her?

00:20:35.610 --> 00:20:36.690
I don't know.

00:20:36.690 --> 00:20:39.050
Let's go, Ferguson.

00:20:39.050 --> 00:20:40.850
Clarissa, I don't see anything.

00:20:40.850 --> 00:20:42.290
Oh, well, you must have gotten it.

00:20:42.290 --> 00:20:43.770
I feel so much better.

00:20:43.770 --> 00:20:45.810
Great, but I don't think I did anything.

00:20:45.810 --> 00:20:47.690
Must have been an eyelash.

00:20:47.690 --> 00:20:50.130
You just have that magic mom touch.

00:20:51.410 --> 00:20:53.570
Hey, Mom, do you think the shirt goes with this,

00:20:53.570 --> 00:20:55.850
or should I change it to that green one?

00:20:55.850 --> 00:20:58.530
Since when do you need help picking out your clothes?

00:20:58.530 --> 00:21:01.130
A girl always needs her mom's clothes advice.

00:21:01.130 --> 00:21:03.010
I may not always follow it, but let's just

00:21:03.010 --> 00:21:06.490
say I'm finally mature enough to admit how much I need it.

00:21:06.490 --> 00:21:08.970
Clarissa, if anything, I would go to you for clothes advice.

00:21:08.970 --> 00:21:10.850
You've already left me way behind.

00:21:10.850 --> 00:21:11.930
No, I haven't.

00:21:11.930 --> 00:21:15.470
What do you mean?

00:21:15.470 --> 00:21:17.430
You are the best cook around here.

00:21:17.430 --> 00:21:20.750
I don't know what I'd do if it wasn't for your neck for food.

00:21:20.750 --> 00:21:24.350
Do you think maybe you could pack my lunch for me tomorrow?

00:21:24.350 --> 00:21:26.750
I stopped packing your lunches for you years ago.

00:21:26.750 --> 00:21:29.110
How about once for old times' sake?

00:21:29.110 --> 00:21:31.190
Well, Clarissa, I think it's better if you do it for yourself.

00:21:31.190 --> 00:21:32.790
That way you get the things you like.

00:21:32.790 --> 00:21:34.910
Mom, let's get something straight.

00:21:34.910 --> 00:21:36.430
Uh-huh.

00:21:36.430 --> 00:21:45.390
I need a glass of milk.

00:21:45.390 --> 00:21:47.030
Yeah, a glass of milk.

00:21:47.030 --> 00:21:59.190
Don't watch for plan A. I guess

00:21:59.190 --> 00:22:01.190
she's just so busy showering herself with attention

00:22:01.190 --> 00:22:02.910
that she's not getting from anywhere else,

00:22:02.910 --> 00:22:06.350
that she doesn't need any attention from me.

00:22:06.350 --> 00:22:10.450
Hi, Sam.

00:22:10.450 --> 00:22:11.770
Hey, Clarissa.

00:22:11.770 --> 00:22:13.930
How this?

00:22:13.930 --> 00:22:17.450
Tommy's tougher high.

00:22:17.450 --> 00:22:20.790
Tommy's tougher high.

00:22:20.790 --> 00:22:27.350
Tommy, Tommy, Tommy, Tommy, Tommy, Tommy's tougher high.

00:22:27.350 --> 00:22:30.390
Definitely hip-er, but can't it stand the test of time?

00:22:30.390 --> 00:22:32.630
Well, honestly, it could be the start of a whole new song

00:22:32.630 --> 00:22:33.670
cycle.

00:22:33.670 --> 00:22:36.510
Tommy's tougher, the high school wizard.

00:22:36.510 --> 00:22:37.830
Can't even go on Broadway.

00:22:37.830 --> 00:22:40.070
Could be a sensation.

00:22:40.070 --> 00:22:41.070
Well, I got an idea.

00:22:41.070 --> 00:22:42.510
Let's go downstairs and ask my mom.

00:22:42.510 --> 00:22:43.870
Your mom?

00:22:43.870 --> 00:22:46.710
Well, she's still singing E&S blues.

00:22:46.710 --> 00:22:48.950
Look, Sam, every day is now Mother's Day

00:22:48.950 --> 00:22:50.870
in the House of Darling.

00:22:50.870 --> 00:22:52.070
I tried to make her feel needed,

00:22:52.070 --> 00:22:54.030
but I think all I did was confuse her.

00:22:54.030 --> 00:22:55.990
I think you should just talk to her.

00:22:55.990 --> 00:22:56.630
I tried.

00:22:56.630 --> 00:22:58.270
She's so distracted.

00:22:58.270 --> 00:22:59.870
Well, why not just tell her to save E&S

00:22:59.870 --> 00:23:02.030
for when the nest is really empty?

00:23:02.030 --> 00:23:04.190
You're right, she's got premature E&S.

00:23:04.190 --> 00:23:05.550
She'll snap out of it.

00:23:05.550 --> 00:23:07.590
Look, I've got to clean up my nest.

00:23:07.590 --> 00:23:08.870
Me and my room.

00:23:08.870 --> 00:23:09.830
Bye, Clarissa.

00:23:09.830 --> 00:23:14.360
Bye, Sam.

00:23:14.360 --> 00:23:17.040
I guess the nest will really be empty soon enough.

00:23:17.040 --> 00:23:18.600
I'll be going to college.

00:23:18.600 --> 00:23:20.680
I'll be living away from home hundreds, maybe

00:23:20.680 --> 00:23:22.360
thousands of miles away.

00:23:22.360 --> 00:23:24.680
Never to come home to roost again.

00:23:24.680 --> 00:23:25.840
The rain.

00:23:25.840 --> 00:23:27.920
I'll always remember the rain.

00:23:27.920 --> 00:23:32.240
Standing there, afraid to go, afraid to stay.

00:23:32.240 --> 00:23:36.920
It seemed to wash away all thought, all time, all my life.

00:23:36.920 --> 00:23:39.920
And finally, I could see the world clearly,

00:23:39.920 --> 00:23:43.480
finally, when it would do me no good.

00:23:43.480 --> 00:23:49.920
Clarissa, I made you this pound cake.

00:23:49.920 --> 00:23:50.880
Hope it's all right.

00:23:50.880 --> 00:23:52.600
I only have half a pound of sugar.

00:23:52.600 --> 00:23:54.600
Mother, you didn't need to do that.

00:23:54.600 --> 00:23:55.360
I know.

00:23:55.360 --> 00:23:57.880
You don't need me to do anything for you anymore.

00:23:57.880 --> 00:23:59.600
You can do it all for yourself.

00:23:59.600 --> 00:24:01.480
Now that's just foolishness.

00:24:01.480 --> 00:24:05.720
My visit was only yesterday you were so tiny.

00:24:05.720 --> 00:24:11.880
My little girl, and now, and now, and now you're all grown up.

00:24:11.880 --> 00:24:14.680
You must be strong.

00:24:14.680 --> 00:24:17.400
Let me dry your tears.

00:24:17.400 --> 00:24:21.380
Be your little girl.

00:24:21.380 --> 00:24:23.660
This will always be home.

00:24:23.660 --> 00:24:27.220
And I will always have time for you.

00:24:27.220 --> 00:24:29.620
Mother, I have to go.

00:24:29.620 --> 00:24:31.820
I can't say goodbye.

00:24:31.860 --> 00:24:34.060
I can't say, or a voile.

00:24:39.060 --> 00:24:52.820
Please don't touch for you.

00:24:52.820 --> 00:24:53.660
You grow up.

00:24:53.660 --> 00:24:55.540
You start doing everything for yourself.

00:24:55.540 --> 00:24:57.500
You leave home to make it on your own.

00:24:57.500 --> 00:24:59.860
Hey, is that any way to treat a mom?

00:24:59.860 --> 00:25:01.540
Why didn't I think of this before?

00:25:01.540 --> 00:25:04.740
If my mom has a premature case of empty nest syndrome,

00:25:04.740 --> 00:25:09.140
I must have a premature case of LNS, leaving nest syndrome.

00:25:09.140 --> 00:25:11.460
Is this a contagious disease or what?

00:25:11.460 --> 00:25:13.300
I better spend some quality time with my mom

00:25:13.300 --> 00:25:15.420
before our time together is over.

00:25:15.420 --> 00:25:24.100
And my premature LNS gets even worse.

00:25:24.100 --> 00:25:26.380
Hi, Carissa.

00:25:26.380 --> 00:25:28.500
You sure are spending a lot of time up here.

00:25:28.500 --> 00:25:30.380
Oh, it's just something I'm working on.

00:25:30.380 --> 00:25:31.220
I know, Mom.

00:25:31.220 --> 00:25:32.180
I understand.

00:25:32.180 --> 00:25:34.820
And Mom, I was just wondering if maybe we

00:25:34.820 --> 00:25:38.700
could spend some more quality time together.

00:25:38.700 --> 00:25:39.980
Quality time?

00:25:39.980 --> 00:25:41.300
Yeah, you know.

00:25:41.300 --> 00:25:43.620
Girl to girl, woman to woman, mother to daughter,

00:25:43.620 --> 00:25:44.940
that kind of thing.

00:25:44.980 --> 00:25:50.970
Oh, well, sure.

00:25:50.970 --> 00:25:53.840
What should we do?

00:25:53.840 --> 00:25:55.280
Maybe we should just talk.

00:25:55.280 --> 00:25:58.650
Great idea.

00:25:58.650 --> 00:26:01.250
So what do you want to talk about?

00:26:01.250 --> 00:26:04.730
I don't know.

00:26:04.730 --> 00:26:07.010
What about Mobius strips?

00:26:07.010 --> 00:26:07.930
Mobius strips?

00:26:07.930 --> 00:26:08.850
What about them?

00:26:08.850 --> 00:26:10.850
You know what's so cool about them?

00:26:10.850 --> 00:26:12.610
That there's no inside or outside,

00:26:12.610 --> 00:26:13.770
that there's only one side?

00:26:13.770 --> 00:26:14.810
Yeah.

00:26:14.810 --> 00:26:17.610
Do you know that reminds me of my very first boyfriend?

00:26:17.610 --> 00:26:19.050
Timmy Hackensash.

00:26:19.050 --> 00:26:20.410
My sixth great sweetheart.

00:26:20.410 --> 00:26:22.450
He really was into origami.

00:26:22.450 --> 00:26:24.250
So I folded up this note to him.

00:26:24.250 --> 00:26:27.850
Only by mistake, I wrote the note on the back of my homework.

00:26:27.850 --> 00:26:28.930
Do you like it?

00:26:28.930 --> 00:26:30.050
I don't remember.

00:26:30.050 --> 00:26:32.530
But it's the first time I got a bad mark for neatness.

00:26:32.530 --> 00:26:34.410
Can you believe it?

00:26:34.410 --> 00:26:35.890
I just remembered.

00:26:35.890 --> 00:26:37.890
I had a dream last night about math.

00:26:37.890 --> 00:26:41.090
I was a fraction on the run from an eraser.

00:26:41.090 --> 00:26:42.970
Wow, how astray.

00:26:42.970 --> 00:26:45.170
You have the most amazing imagination.

00:26:45.170 --> 00:26:46.890
Actually, we were all fractions.

00:26:46.890 --> 00:26:51.210
You, me, Dad, Bergson, I wonder what it means.

00:26:51.210 --> 00:26:54.170
Well, dreams are so strange that...

00:26:54.170 --> 00:26:55.370
I've got it.

00:26:55.370 --> 00:26:56.250
What?

00:26:56.250 --> 00:26:58.330
Well, in my dream, we were all different fractions.

00:26:58.330 --> 00:27:02.890
But together, we added up to a whole, a unit, a family.

00:27:02.890 --> 00:27:04.410
What a nice thought.

00:27:04.410 --> 00:27:06.490
Sometimes isn't everything just great.

00:27:06.490 --> 00:27:09.330
Yeah, it's nice to see you feeling so, um...

00:27:09.330 --> 00:27:10.570
Great?

00:27:10.570 --> 00:27:12.970
Yeah, it's great.

00:27:12.970 --> 00:27:15.130
Now, I really better get going.

00:27:15.130 --> 00:27:16.770
Going? Where are you going?

00:27:16.770 --> 00:27:18.890
Oh, I just have to drop something off.

00:27:18.890 --> 00:27:20.890
But we just sat down together.

00:27:20.930 --> 00:27:22.650
Clarissa, I'll be back.

00:27:22.650 --> 00:27:26.090
But you've been so busy, and I just wanted to spend some time with you.

00:27:26.090 --> 00:27:28.010
Well, usually, you're the one who's so busy.

00:27:28.010 --> 00:27:30.850
I know, and I'm sorry, and...

00:27:30.850 --> 00:27:32.930
I won't forget any more of your stuff, and...

00:27:32.930 --> 00:27:34.490
and it's not that you don't matter anymore.

00:27:34.490 --> 00:27:37.770
What? Really? It's fine. I'm pretty busy myself.

00:27:37.770 --> 00:27:38.970
Now, I really better get going.

00:27:38.970 --> 00:27:41.330
Well, where are you going? I'll go with you.

00:27:41.330 --> 00:27:43.690
Clarissa, we can spend some time together later.

00:27:43.690 --> 00:27:47.090
Later? Later? Soon it'll be too late.

00:27:47.090 --> 00:27:49.170
Dear, what's gotten into you?

00:27:49.170 --> 00:27:50.690
Don't get so worked up.

00:27:50.690 --> 00:27:54.850
Look, if you'd really like, you can help me deliver this basket to Mrs. Flinchrod.

00:27:54.850 --> 00:27:57.170
Mrs. Flinchrod?

00:27:57.170 --> 00:27:59.090
Who's Mrs. Flinchrod?

00:27:59.090 --> 00:28:03.370
You know her. She's that very sweet old lady who volunteered for the children's museum.

00:28:03.370 --> 00:28:05.890
And she's been ill some time now, and...

00:28:05.890 --> 00:28:09.850
lately she took a turn for the worse, so she needed some extra cheering up.

00:28:09.850 --> 00:28:13.770
And the kids and I have been making her gifts and bringing her little surprises.

00:28:13.770 --> 00:28:15.290
Oh.

00:28:15.290 --> 00:28:19.850
She's been such a great mom to all of us, and we want her to know she's appreciated.

00:28:19.890 --> 00:28:22.450
So all the cards and flowers were for...

00:28:22.450 --> 00:28:23.970
Mrs. Flinchrod.

00:28:23.970 --> 00:28:28.770
Oh. In other words, all this stuff you've been preoccupied with is kind of like a

00:28:28.770 --> 00:28:31.450
every day's Mother's Day for Mrs. Flinchrod sort of thing?

00:28:31.450 --> 00:28:34.890
She's a great lady. It's a shame she's not feeling well.

00:28:34.890 --> 00:28:35.890
You can come along.

00:28:35.890 --> 00:28:36.970
Sure.

00:28:36.970 --> 00:28:39.570
And all this time I thought you were suffering from ENF.

00:28:39.570 --> 00:28:40.490
What?

00:28:40.490 --> 00:28:44.810
You know, empty nest syndrome because someday I'm gonna leave home and you're gonna miss me.

00:28:44.810 --> 00:28:47.850
I will miss you and you will leave home someday, and...

00:28:47.850 --> 00:28:53.170
Who knows? Go to college, travel around the world in a balloon, maybe get married.

00:28:53.170 --> 00:28:55.250
But you're not gonna do it tomorrow, are you?

00:28:55.250 --> 00:28:57.850
Me? Boy, I hope not.

00:28:57.850 --> 00:28:59.170
Well, I better get going.

00:28:59.170 --> 00:29:00.530
To Mrs. Flinchrod's edit.

00:29:00.530 --> 00:29:01.570
Wait, I'm coming.

00:29:01.570 --> 00:29:08.580
This ENF thing is just something we're gonna have to get through together.

00:29:08.580 --> 00:29:10.300
Janet?

00:29:10.300 --> 00:29:11.700
Oh.

00:29:11.700 --> 00:29:13.980
Is that the old rocker from my college store?

00:29:13.980 --> 00:29:15.300
Yeah, doesn't it look great?

00:29:15.300 --> 00:29:16.540
It really does.

00:29:16.540 --> 00:29:19.940
Yeah. First it looked old, now it looks antique.

00:29:19.940 --> 00:29:23.060
I think this quaint old thing could fetch a pretty penny.

00:29:23.060 --> 00:29:25.860
Nice idea, Ferguson, but you're not selling it.

00:29:25.860 --> 00:29:28.100
Oh, Mom, you didn't even know you had it.

00:29:28.100 --> 00:29:30.540
But now I do. This is great.

00:29:30.540 --> 00:29:32.900
This chair took 28 lemonade breaks.

00:29:32.900 --> 00:29:37.860
Well, it will be just perfect for my old age when the kids leave home once you're hurry.

00:29:37.860 --> 00:29:39.340
So, how'd your school anthem go?

00:29:39.340 --> 00:29:40.580
It was a big hit.

00:29:40.580 --> 00:29:43.380
This is a Thomas. Thomas told me what's the deal.

00:29:43.380 --> 00:29:45.740
We've got you on our minds from the lockers to the fields.

00:29:45.740 --> 00:29:48.500
Since you gotta go to school, Thomas' supper is no place.

00:29:48.500 --> 00:29:50.740
So when we graduate, we'll be out of your face.

00:29:50.740 --> 00:29:52.660
Oh, that's great.

00:29:52.660 --> 00:29:55.780
You know, you two songwriters might really be going places.

00:29:55.780 --> 00:29:56.980
Don't rush us, Mom.

00:29:56.980 --> 00:29:58.940
Right now, I'm staying right here.

00:34:29.860 --> 00:34:36.100
This is the Crafts Built 2000, also known as the Gashmaster.

00:34:36.100 --> 00:34:44.420
Its 17-inch blade with 248 steel teeth can slice a telephone pole in half in 9.2 seconds.

00:34:44.420 --> 00:34:50.980
The way I see it, anything with 248 teeth should not be allowed in a school.

00:34:50.980 --> 00:34:59.660
If you screw up using the Crafts Built 2000 or the Neurtron F7 grinder or the Impreg rotary lathe,

00:34:59.660 --> 00:35:04.180
best case, you'll go home minus a thorax.

00:35:04.180 --> 00:35:07.060
You see, my philosophy is simple.

00:35:07.060 --> 00:35:12.460
In a world where there are literally 10 million ways to mutilate yourself on a normal day,

00:35:12.580 --> 00:35:15.380
why go messing around with tools?

00:35:15.380 --> 00:35:20.420
It was a philosophy that I based my entire life and school schedule around.

00:35:20.420 --> 00:35:28.020
That is, until one fateful day last spring, when the school schedule gods were in the mood to bust my clams.

00:35:28.020 --> 00:35:33.700
Because when my new schedule arrived, I saw the one word that I prayed I'd never see.

00:35:33.700 --> 00:35:47.980
Shop.

00:35:47.980 --> 00:36:41.630
I can't be sadder than she'd been for having been in the dark and thin.

00:36:41.630 --> 00:36:42.910
Tools.

00:36:42.910 --> 00:36:44.070
They're loud.

00:36:44.070 --> 00:36:45.150
They're sharp.

00:36:45.150 --> 00:36:46.830
And they can kill you.

00:36:46.830 --> 00:36:51.070
And what do you end up with after risking your limbs in life?

00:36:51.070 --> 00:36:52.910
A spice rack.

00:36:52.910 --> 00:36:56.590
Is there anything more pointless in life than a spice rack?

00:36:56.590 --> 00:37:03.270
And is making a spice rack worth the loss of a body part that I've come to know and love?

00:37:03.270 --> 00:37:06.630
Obviously the schedule gods must think so.

00:37:06.630 --> 00:37:09.950
Either that or they're into spicy food.

00:37:09.950 --> 00:37:15.670
And that's where my story begins, in the dungeon that I shot.

00:37:15.670 --> 00:37:16.870
Real funny.

00:37:16.870 --> 00:37:19.870
Put my head into a vise.

00:37:19.870 --> 00:37:21.430
Can you take it out now?

00:37:21.430 --> 00:37:22.870
It's so funny.

00:37:22.870 --> 00:37:27.610
Why aren't you laughing, corn boy?

00:37:27.610 --> 00:37:30.970
Mike, please don't put his head in the vise.

00:37:30.970 --> 00:37:32.930
What are you, his dad?

00:37:32.930 --> 00:37:37.170
As a matter of fact, I am his dad.

00:37:37.170 --> 00:37:38.890
Oh.

00:37:38.930 --> 00:37:45.850
Luckily, like a lot of Socketheads, Endless Mike Hellstrom was very easy to confuse.

00:37:45.850 --> 00:37:50.050
He was one of those high school lifers who always seemed to be in shop.

00:37:50.050 --> 00:37:51.290
You know the type.

00:37:51.290 --> 00:37:54.210
Guys with names like Harley and Fleck.

00:37:54.210 --> 00:37:57.410
Well, here's something you might not have known.

00:37:57.410 --> 00:38:01.450
Socketheads rule their turf.

00:38:01.450 --> 00:38:03.930
You need a tool.

00:38:03.930 --> 00:38:06.920
You come to me.

00:38:06.920 --> 00:38:09.840
You need a nut.

00:38:09.840 --> 00:38:15.940
Nail, screw, bolt, nut.

00:38:15.940 --> 00:38:18.700
You come to me.

00:38:18.700 --> 00:38:24.180
You need a safety goggles or a helmet.

00:38:24.180 --> 00:38:28.020
You come to me.

00:38:28.020 --> 00:38:34.900
And maybe you pay attention and you follow the rules of the class.

00:38:34.900 --> 00:38:41.770
Mr. Slurm, he might let you work on a special project.

00:38:41.770 --> 00:38:43.210
Questions?

00:38:43.210 --> 00:38:46.580
What's a special project?

00:38:46.580 --> 00:38:53.490
If you deserve to know.

00:38:53.490 --> 00:38:55.450
What's that supposed to mean?

00:38:55.450 --> 00:38:56.810
Who cares?

00:38:56.810 --> 00:39:00.610
I don't want to have anything to do with Slurm's special project.

00:39:00.610 --> 00:39:06.650
I'm just going to sit in the back, get my C, and see you later shop class.

00:39:06.650 --> 00:39:09.130
Now, I heard all about Slurm's special project.

00:39:09.130 --> 00:39:12.970
It's a cryogenic freezer who wants to freeze his own head when he dies.

00:39:12.970 --> 00:39:14.290
Really?

00:39:14.290 --> 00:39:18.410
Uh-uh, it's an anti-ballistic fragmentary explosive.

00:39:18.410 --> 00:39:20.050
What, you guys never heard of those?

00:39:20.090 --> 00:39:22.690
Teddy, you can't make a bomb in shop class.

00:39:22.690 --> 00:39:23.970
Want to bet?

00:39:23.970 --> 00:39:29.960
Besides, I heard that Slurm wants to get the guy back who?

00:39:29.960 --> 00:39:35.000
Oh yeah, there was something I forgot to tell you about Mr. Slurm.

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:38.840
Nobody knew how he lost it, but just like his special project,

00:39:38.840 --> 00:39:41.400
practically everyone had a theory.

00:39:41.400 --> 00:39:44.360
I already cut it off himself so we could be part tool.

00:39:44.360 --> 00:39:45.760
Uh-uh, landmine.

00:39:45.760 --> 00:39:48.320
We're calling Delta 67.

00:39:48.320 --> 00:39:51.440
Another theory was that Slurm made his claw

00:39:51.440 --> 00:39:59.540
and all its attachments himself in shop class.

00:39:59.540 --> 00:40:04.640
Wood, theory and practice.

00:40:04.640 --> 00:40:07.560
I couldn't believe that I actually had to sit there

00:40:07.560 --> 00:40:13.600
and listen to this ratchet brain babble on about wood.

00:40:13.600 --> 00:40:19.660
And what was the story with all those attachments?

00:40:19.660 --> 00:40:22.740
And I couldn't figure out whether everyone else had been lulled

00:40:22.740 --> 00:40:26.420
into a hypnotic trance by Slurm's sideshow

00:40:26.420 --> 00:40:34.430
or if they were seriously into it.

00:40:34.470 --> 00:40:38.470
Perhaps you could tell us the most sullen wood

00:40:38.470 --> 00:40:47.740
we've discussed so far, Mr. Wrigley.

00:40:47.740 --> 00:40:52.610
Nagahide?

00:40:52.610 --> 00:40:56.300
Mahogany?

00:40:56.300 --> 00:41:02.310
Uh, I mean, walnut?

00:41:02.310 --> 00:41:04.670
So much for vanishing.

00:41:04.670 --> 00:41:07.390
Right then I decided that I had too much at stake

00:41:07.390 --> 00:41:09.110
to cross this guy.

00:41:09.110 --> 00:41:13.990
It was only the first day and already Slurm had me pegged.

00:41:13.990 --> 00:41:16.390
But while one Pete was busted,

00:41:16.390 --> 00:41:21.140
the other Pete was in business.

00:41:21.140 --> 00:41:23.420
When he heard I was taking shop,

00:41:23.420 --> 00:41:28.600
he took an after-school job as an insurance salesman.

00:41:28.600 --> 00:41:33.400
Boys, when you least expect it, expect it.

00:41:33.400 --> 00:41:35.880
But Pete wasn't selling car insurance

00:41:35.880 --> 00:41:37.840
or homeowners insurance.

00:41:37.840 --> 00:41:40.840
Pete was in the dismemberment business.

00:41:40.840 --> 00:41:43.640
He had a chart that showed every body part

00:41:43.640 --> 00:41:46.320
and their value in cash and merchandise.

00:41:46.320 --> 00:41:49.320
Bill was the only one who bit Pete's bait.

00:41:49.320 --> 00:41:51.960
I sure didn't, because there was no way

00:41:51.960 --> 00:41:54.880
that I was even going near the power tools.

00:41:54.880 --> 00:41:57.720
The Craftsbilt is not a toy.

00:41:57.720 --> 00:42:03.110
And it is not just a tool.

00:42:03.110 --> 00:42:06.750
It is the Cadillac of sores.

00:42:06.750 --> 00:42:09.470
Use it carefully.

00:42:09.470 --> 00:42:12.430
12 years ago, a Mr. Naby didn't.

00:42:12.430 --> 00:42:16.390
One hair of his got caught around the Craftsbilt

00:42:16.390 --> 00:42:20.870
patented acu-chrome spinning drive shaft.

00:42:20.870 --> 00:42:25.700
The rest of his scalp quickly followed.

00:42:25.700 --> 00:42:31.900
Who'd like to cut something with the TS-4?

00:42:31.900 --> 00:42:42.660
Or as you'll soon be calling it, ah, yes.

00:42:42.660 --> 00:42:44.620
How about?

00:42:44.620 --> 00:42:50.110
I will, Mr. Slurm.

00:42:50.110 --> 00:42:54.310
Thankfully, Ellen saved my thorax for the moment.

00:42:54.310 --> 00:42:56.510
But what I didn't know was that Ellen

00:42:56.510 --> 00:42:58.470
wasn't really saving me.

00:42:58.470 --> 00:43:01.750
She was leaving me, because within a week,

00:43:01.750 --> 00:43:08.400
Ellen had turned into a slur-moy.

00:43:08.400 --> 00:43:10.120
Did you know that a blowtorch burns

00:43:10.120 --> 00:43:16.850
with the same intensity as the Earth's core?

00:43:16.850 --> 00:43:21.490
If you stare into the flame long enough, you can see its soul.

00:43:21.490 --> 00:43:23.970
Want to look, Pete?

00:43:23.970 --> 00:43:27.850
I knew that Ellen had a history of going a little, well,

00:43:27.850 --> 00:43:29.490
overboard at times.

00:43:29.490 --> 00:43:31.610
But this was ridiculous.

00:43:31.610 --> 00:43:33.970
I don't think of it as melting the metal.

00:43:33.970 --> 00:43:38.250
I think of it as setting it free.

00:43:38.250 --> 00:43:50.950
The adventures of Pete and Pete will be right back on Snack.

00:43:50.950 --> 00:43:51.950
Nuts and honey?

00:43:51.950 --> 00:43:53.430
Oh, I bet I can.

00:43:53.430 --> 00:43:57.670
It's a break for the taste of honey nut Cheerios.

00:43:57.670 --> 00:43:59.550
Part of this complete breakfast.

00:43:59.550 --> 00:44:00.550
A win.

00:44:00.550 --> 00:44:03.780
Yeah, but losing.

00:44:03.780 --> 00:44:06.140
Never tasted so sweet.

00:44:06.140 --> 00:44:07.180
So where's the bee?

00:44:07.180 --> 00:44:09.580
You can look real hard, and he'll magically appear

00:44:09.580 --> 00:44:11.820
in these 3D pictures on the back of Mark's boxes

00:44:11.820 --> 00:44:14.060
of honey nut Cheerios.

00:44:14.060 --> 00:44:17.220
You know what happened to Stanley Ipkis

00:44:17.220 --> 00:44:19.340
when he put on the mask?

00:44:19.340 --> 00:44:20.980
OK.

00:44:20.980 --> 00:44:26.380
But wait till you see what happens to his dog Milo.

00:44:26.380 --> 00:44:28.620
Together, get your dog away from me.

00:44:28.620 --> 00:44:30.180
Sorry, it seems to be attracted to you.

00:44:30.180 --> 00:44:35.900
They're taking a fight out of crime.

00:44:35.900 --> 00:44:38.060
Jim Carrey is the mask.

00:44:38.060 --> 00:44:40.060
This has got to be a new breed.

00:44:40.060 --> 00:44:45.390
Rated PG-13, now playing everywhere.

00:44:45.390 --> 00:44:47.670
No, but I got you some of your own.

00:44:47.670 --> 00:44:48.670
Caution.

00:44:48.670 --> 00:44:50.670
These tools look real.

00:44:50.670 --> 00:44:51.670
Cool tools.

00:44:51.670 --> 00:44:52.670
Look at the bee.

00:44:52.670 --> 00:44:53.670
Cool tools.

00:44:53.670 --> 00:44:54.670
Cool, cool, cool.

00:44:54.670 --> 00:44:55.670
Cool tools.

00:44:55.670 --> 00:44:57.670
Ready for real metal tools?

00:44:57.670 --> 00:44:59.670
You can get cool tools.

00:44:59.670 --> 00:45:01.670
Keep them in your handy tool belt or in your cool tools

00:45:01.670 --> 00:45:02.670
toolbox.

00:45:02.670 --> 00:45:04.670
You got my tape measure.

00:45:04.670 --> 00:45:05.670
Uh, that's it.

00:45:05.670 --> 00:45:06.670
Yeah.

00:45:06.670 --> 00:45:07.670
Cool, cool, cool.

00:45:07.670 --> 00:45:08.670
Cool tools.

00:45:08.670 --> 00:45:09.670
Cool tools.

00:45:09.670 --> 00:45:11.670
Tools, belt, and toolbox.

00:45:11.670 --> 00:45:13.670
Each sold separately, batteries not included.

00:45:13.670 --> 00:45:16.670
Now, back to the adventures of Pete and Pete as

00:45:16.670 --> 00:45:17.670
we continue.

00:45:17.670 --> 00:45:25.580
It didn't take long for me to realize that I was the only

00:45:25.580 --> 00:45:28.580
kid in that class who just wanted to get a seat and

00:45:28.580 --> 00:45:34.140
get out of shop forever.

00:45:34.140 --> 00:45:41.740
It's Danish modern.

00:45:41.740 --> 00:45:47.180
That is, until our midterm projects were due.

00:45:47.180 --> 00:45:49.180
You were once a kid.

00:45:49.180 --> 00:45:50.180
Deep.

00:45:50.180 --> 00:45:54.180
You see, Slurm had his own way of grading.

00:45:54.180 --> 00:45:55.180
Airless.

00:45:55.180 --> 00:45:56.180
Airless.

00:45:56.180 --> 00:45:57.180
C minus.

00:45:57.180 --> 00:46:04.240
The caligari technique.

00:46:04.240 --> 00:46:06.240
Very good young lady.

00:46:06.240 --> 00:46:07.240
B plus.

00:46:07.240 --> 00:46:12.720
He liked it, Pete.

00:46:12.720 --> 00:46:15.720
But you'll get to work on a special project.

